=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



Workshop on Analogies: from Theory to Applications (ATA@ICCBR 2022)



Call For Papers



Date: September 12th, 2022



Location: Nancy, France



Website: https://iccbr-ata2022.loria.fr/



Important dates:



* June 12, 2022: Workshop Paper Due Date

* July 3, 2022: Notification of Paper Acceptance

* July 17, 2022: Camera-ready papers due



=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



Analogical proportions, i.e., statements of the form "A is to B as C is to =
D", are the basis of analogical inference and they are closely related to c=
ase-based reasoning and transfer learning.

They are have been used on NLP tasks such as automatic machine translation,=
 semantic and morphological tasks, as well as visual question answering wit=
h competitive results.

Moreover, analogical reasoning can support several machine learning tasks s=
uch as classification, decision making, or dataset augmentation.

However, other less explored applications could be envisioned such as knowl=
edge discovery and management (e.g., knowledge graphs refinement, data set =
completion, and alignment), recommender systems, and other AI-related tasks=
 such as explainable AI.



The purpose of this workshop is thus to explore both foundational and appli=
cative aspects of analogical reasoning in various fields, e.g., machine lea=
rning, knowledge representation, discovery, and reasoning, as well as in in=
dustry practice with real-world data, applications, and associated challeng=
es, for instance, scalability issues.



=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



Themes and topics



=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



We invite submissions of research papers on the foundational theory of anal=
ogies, on interactions between case-based reasoning and analogies, as well =
as on applicative use-case studies.

Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:



* Foundational theory of analogies:

    - Axiomatic approaches to analogical proportions;

    - Analogy-preserving functions;

    - Interactions between case-based and analogical reasoning.



* Applications:

    - Analogical reasoning in machine learning;

    - Analogical reasoning in visual domains;

    - Analogical reasoning in Natural Language Processing;

    - Analogical reasoning in healthcare;

    - Analogy based explanations;

    - Analogies in software engineering;

    - Analogies in knowledge management.





=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



Submission Guidelines



=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



Submitted papers must be formatted according to Springer LNCS formatting gu=
idelines, see:

https://iccbr2022.loria.fr/call-for-papers/



We welcome contributions in the form of extended abstracts (up to two pages=
 + 1 page for references) and long papers (up to six pages + 1 page for ref=
erences).

Submissions can describe either work in progress or mature work.



All papers will be  thoroughly reviewed (single-blind).

Overlength and/or out-of-scope papers will be rejected without review.





=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



Proceedings



=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



All papers will appear in the pre-proceedings made available on the worksho=
p webpage.

Original contributions will be published as proposed by ICCBR 2022.





=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D



